I am a Ph.D. candidate in the Division of Computer, Electrical and Mathematical Science and Engineering at KAUST, Saudi Arabia. Previously, I was with the Data Science team at Mozn, an analytics and big data technologies company based in Riyadh.

My interest includes designing charging infrastructure for electric vehicles (EVs) and building applied-machine learning data products. 

Some projects I have done and am currently doing are
- Designing dynamic charging systems, i.e., roads with charging capability, for EVs (Top 4 of the IET #PresentIn10 competition - Sustainability theme)
- Developing Focal- a sanction screening software that stops suspicious individuals from infiltrating financial institutions using NLP focusing on Arabic inputs (with Mozn)
- Designing a model using graph neural network to predict path delay in computer networking (Rank 5/51 teams participated in the 2020 ITU Graph Neural Networking Challenge)
- Identifying clusters-of-interest based on spatial-textual information of social media messages

Details and source codes of some of my projects are available on my Google Scholar and GitHub.

In 2018, I was selected to be the recipient of two full scholarships, i.e., the Erasmus Mundus Master Programme in Big Data Management and Analytics (TU Berlin, acceptance rate 3%) and University of Helsinki Master Programme in Data Science (acceptance rate 1.3%). However, I declined those opportunities to come to KAUST. Feel free to message me if you need tips on applying for those programs. 

Aside from work, I love playing sports, particularly golf and tennis.

schoolDescription2: High mobility group nucleosome binding (HMGN) proteins belong to the superfamily of high mobility group (HMG) proteins. HMGN1 (N1) and HMGN2 (N2) were found to be highly expressed in neural stem/progenitor cells in the mouse brain. Here, mouse embryonal carcinoma cells (P19 EC) were used as a model system to study the role of HMGN proteins. The aim was to develop a lentiviral system to investigate the role of this protein in stem cell. N2 knockdown in undifferentiated P19 EC cells resulted in the down regulation of Oct4 protein levels. ChIP assays showed that N2 binding over the Oct4 gene was absent in N2 knockdown cells. Furthermore, the binding of N1 at TSS was increased in the absence of N2. Consistent with the reduction in Oct4 expression, the level of the active histone modification, H3K4me3, were also reduced at the Oct4 gene. These results support the role of N2 in the regulation of Oct4 expression in P19 cells which may be important for maintaining stem cell pluripotency.
